annotation.TEXT: Buffalo Bob Smith (b. Robert Schmidt) was host of the NBC children’s series The Howdy Doody Show from 1947-60.
Trick-or-treating dates back to the Middle Ages, when it was called “souling.” The more modern custom, however, traces to 19th-century UK, where it was called “guising.”
An imitation of Manuel (Andrew Sachs), the Spanish waiter in the Torquay, England, hotel Fawlty Towers in the classic BBC sitcom of the same name.
Jacques Cousteau was a French ocean explorer and the inventor of the Aqua-Lung, which helped him in his extensive underwater expeditions.
The Wienermobile is an ad vehicle shaped like a hot dog on a bun, used to promote Oscar Mayer wieners. The first Wienermobile was made in 1936 by Oscar Mayer’s nephew.
“867-5309/Jenny” was a 1982 Top 10 hit by Tommy Tutone. The phone number has caused headaches for people unfortunate enough to be assigned it ever since.
Alexander Calder was an artist best known for his colorful and elaborate mobiles.
While a Chapter 13 bankruptcy filing allows for debt consolidation, it can cause problems for the person’s credit rating for 7 years.
Rubbermaid was founded in 1920 in Ohio by a group of businessmen and named Wooster Rubber. They originally sold balloons.
That would make for about 45 centuries of continuous profitability, given Stonehenge’s construction date of between 3000 and 2000 BCE.
In the ‘80s, Disney ran an ad campaign asking athletes after a triumphant game what they were going to do next, to which they would declare, “I’m going to Disney World!”
Mikhail Gorbachev led the Soviet Union just before its collapse; his term was marked by a desire for more openness (“glasnost”), which eventually led to greater freedoms for the Soviet people.
The Frank Frazetta painting on the cover of Molly Hatchet’s sophomore album Flirtin’ with Disaster depicts a gnarled, muscular warrior with enormous wings on either side of his helmet.
An imitation of any number of game shows, often The Price Is Right, wherein a new car was offered up as the ultimate prize for guessing how much a bottle of shampoo costs.
“I’m Just Wild About Harry” is a song from the 1921 musical Shuffle Along. Harry Truman used it as his presidential campaign song in 1948.
Sesame Street’s Big Bird has been performed by Caroll Spinney since the series began in 1969, with apprentices filling in from time to time in recent years.
When John Landis was directing Twilight Zone: The Movie, a helicopter crash killed three actors, two of them kids. Landis and four others were charged with involuntary manslaughter but acquitted.
Armor All today is owned by Spectrum Brands, the same company that owns the Rayovac, Remington, and George Foreman brands.
Blaupunkt (meaning “blue dot”) is a German manufacturer of high-end electronics founded in 1923.
The Keebler Elves, introduced in ads in 1968, have since become some of the most recognizable ad icons in existence.
Vidal Sassoon was a British hairstylist who often appeared in ads for his products. “If you don’t look good, we don’t look good” was their longtime ad slogan.
Writer L. Ron Hubbard told multiple people in the late ‘40s that the easiest way to make money was to start a religion. Less than 10 years later Scientology was born.
Dr. Scholl’s is a foot care brand started in 1906 by podiatrist William Scholl.
Moon Zero Two: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Discount store chain Kmart became famous for their “Blue Light Specials” in the ‘90s: 15-minute deals announced over the store’s PA system.
“The Wiener Man” is a campfire song popular with scout-aged children.
Rayon is a manmade fiber first produced in the 1890s as an alternative to silk. Naugahyde is a brand of artificial leather first made in Naugatuck, CT (hence the name).
The Community Chest cards in the board game Monopoly were named after a charity by that name; it was the original name for the United Way.
The titular Pink Panther from the Peter Sellers movies, which also featured animated credit sequences, was a large pink diamond that appears in several of the films.
A boxing glove on an extending metal arm is a common trope in comics and cartoons; it was one of the Joker’s standard weapons against Batman.
Dennis Hopper was an actor known for his hippie ways and roles in Easy Rider, Apocalypse Now, and Blue Velvet.
Anheuser-Busch ran ads in the ‘80s in which someone would ask for a light; receive a flashlight, a lightbulb, a match, etc.; and respond with an exasperated “I said ‘Bud Light!’”
Welcome Wagon has been greeting new homeowners with a bundle of coupons and ads from local businesses since 1928.
Hugh Hefner is the founder of Playboy magazine and one of the last bastions of the ‘60s bachelor lifestyle.
“It works every time” was the ‘80s-era slogan for Colt 45 malt liquor.
Looking for Mr. Goodbar is the name of a novel and film about a doomed schoolteacher who picks up men in sleazy bars. It was based on a 1973 murder case.
A lawn jockey is a small statue of an African-American man in horse-racing gear, holding a lantern. They are controversial and often seen as racist, but they are still made and sold.
In the book Peter Pan by J.M. Barrie, Peter tells the children that thinking happy thoughts is the key to flight, but he is lying; in fact, fairy dust is required.
Slush Puppie is a brand of frozen treat, similar to snow cones, sold in gas stations and convenience stores around the country since 1970.
Nintendo revolutionized the home gaming industry in 1985 with the NES, after the gluttonous crash of 1983 (aka “The Atari Debacle”).
Alan Hale Jr., who played the sheriff in MST3K Episode 810, The Giant Spider Invasion, played the Skipper on TV’s Gilligan’s Island. They were famously stranded after “a three-hour tour.”
Bronko Nagurski was a pro football player and heavyweight wrestler in the ‘30s, known for his intimidating size and brute force.
Nine actors have played Darth Vader, including Sebastian Shaw (Return of the Jedi, when his mask is removed), C. Andrew Nelson (extra special edition footage), and Ben Burtt (the breathing).
The conga is a style of Cuban music (and an accompanying dance) introduced to the US by Desi Arnaz in the late ‘30s.
Howie Mandel is a standup comedian and actor who was a regular on the TV series St. Elsewhere and later hosted the game show Deal or No Deal.
On the short-lived TV series Police Squad!, Detective Frank Drebin (played by Leslie Nielsen) always replied, “Yes, it is,” whenever he was offered a smoke.
A brief imitation of Peter Lorre, an actor famous for his appearances in Casablanca and The Maltese Falcon.
The animated film features the music and likenesses of The Beatles, but their voices were performed by other actors. (The Beatles appear as themselves in a live-action epilogue.)
Slurpees are 7-Eleven’s brand of flavored ice drinks. In 1970 the chain gave away a 45 single record titled “Dance the Slurp” with the purchase of a Slurpee.
D-cup is a measurement of breast size dating back to 1932, when the A-D scale was created. The largest natural breasts on record weigh in (literally) at 102ZZZ and 65 lbs. Each.
An oddly prescient line, considering it was spoken in 1990, when Donald Trump was merely a financially troubled real estate developer, rather than a polarizing politician.
The word “yahoo” originated in Jonathan Swift’s satirical novel Gulliver’s Travels, where it was the name of a race of brutish subhumans.
Fozzie Bear (performed by Frank Oz until 2000; Eric Jacobson thereafter) is a Muppet comic who first appeared on The Muppet Show in 1976. “Wocka, wocka, wocka” is his catchphrase.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
The American Automobile Association (AAA) provides roadside assistance to its members. Jump starts are included in the membership fee.
Lines from the end of Pee-wee Herman’s famous 1981 HBO special The Pee-wee Herman Show, when his wish to fly is granted by Jambi the genie.
Lola Falana is a singer and actress who was the highest-paid female performer in Las Vegas in the late ‘70s.
Tupperware is still sold at the “Tupperware parties” famous in the ‘50s, in which a sales representative (usually a woman) makes her pitch to a group gathered at someone’s home.
The British sci-fi series Space: 1999 was also set on a moon base; it starred real-life couple Martin Landau and Barbara Bain.
Possibly a reference to the Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV), first deployed on the Moon’s surface in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission.
Richard Kiel was a 7-foot-tall actor who played the henchman Jaws in two James Bond films. MSTies know and adore him as the prehistoric caveman who just wants to be loved in MST3K Episode 506, Eegah!
Petula Clark is an English singer and actress who had her biggest hit in 1964 with “Downtown.” It has since been covered by artists such as Dolly Parton and The B-52’s.
The image of the man in the Moon is formed by the lunar maria, ancient “seas” of dark basalt. There are various mythological explanations for his presence; medieval Christians believed he was Cain.
Formica is a brand of plastic laminate developed by two Westinghouse engineers in 1912 who were trying to create an artificial replacement for the mineral mica: thus, “for mica.”
Mr. Pibb was first produced in 1972 (under the name “Peppo”) as a rival to Dr Pepper.
Snooper and Blabber was a short cartoon about a cat and mouse detective team on The Quick Draw McGraw Show. Blabber Mouse spoke with a lisp, thus Josh’s imitation.
Blue Meanies are the antagonists in the Beatles film Yellow Submarine who hate music and, essentially, anything good and fun.
“Old Glory” is a nickname for the American flag coined in the 1820s by U.S. ship captain William Driver. The name was originally for his personal flag, now on display at the Smithsonian.
On Hogan’s Heroes, Col. Klink reported to Gen. Burkhalter, before whom Klink would typically be made to look like a fool by the POWs.
The Nintendo Power Glove was an NES controller that re-created hand movements onscreen. The villain in the 1989 Fred Savage film The Wizard famously wielded a Power Glove.
The “Old West” generally refers to the second half of the 19th century, when the US was completing its expansion to the Pacific coast.
Let us know if we missed any references!
“The Far Side” comic by Gary Larson ran in nearly 2,000 newspapers at its peak in the late ‘80s/early ‘90s.
Music to (Whatever) By is a style of album title dating back several decades—the best-selling was probably 1966’s Music to Watch Girls By from The Bob Crewe Generation.
French cuffs are a style of extra-long shirt sleeve cuffs, usually regarded as formal wear and requiring cuff links to keep them closed.
Although considered one of the greatest baseball players ever, Pete Rose has been disgraced by admitting to betting on baseball, including his own games.
Thumbelina is the heroine of a Hans Christian Andersen fairy tale about a woman who wishes for a child and gets one about the size of a thumb.
Actress Goldie Hawn played the “dim blonde” stereotype to the hilt on the sketch comedy show Rowan & Martin’s Laugh-In, where she was known for her trademark giggle and her skimpy bikini.
Space Mountain is the name of Disney theme parks’ popular space-themed indoor roller coasters; some were retooled as “Hyperspace Mountains” after Disney bought Star Wars.
Foosball was invented by Englishman Harold Searles Thornton in 1922; his initial mockup consisted of laying matches across the top of a matchbox.
In 2001 Mr. Pibb was renamed Pibb Xtra and slightly reformulated with added cinnamon. (However, Crow explicitly said, “Anything but Mr. Pibb.”)
Throughout his time as the Colt 45 spokesman, Williams brushed off criticism about marketing malt liquor to low-income audiences, as well as claims that the ads focused on getting women drunk.
Playtex has made gloves since the ‘50s, later branded “Playtex Living Gloves.” Coincidentally, Playtex made spacesuits for NASA in the ‘60s, including the one Neil Armstrong wore on the Moon.
“Up, Up and Away” is a 1967 song also released by The 5th Dimension; it reached the Top 10.
Jack Daniel’s (sometimes abbreviated as just “Jack” or “JD”) is a brand of Tennessee whiskey, first produced by founder Jack Daniel in 1875 (although the label claims 1866).
Fidel Castro is the longtime socialist leader of Cuba. He stepped aside as Cuba’s president in 2008, handing the reins to his brother, Raúl.
Peter and the Wolf by Sergei Prokofiev is famous for using instrumental leitmotifs for each character. The strings represent Peter, for instance, while the French horns play the Wolf.
Borscht Belt-style comedian Norm Crosby is known for his malapropisms, such as drinking “decapitated” coffee and speaking from his “diagram.”
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration took over from its predecessor, the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA), amidst alarm over the Soviet launch of Sputnik.
“Old Mother Hubbard” is an English nursery rhyme first printed in 1805 about an elderly matron searching for a treat to appease her canine.
In the olden days, department store elevator operators often announced to the passengers what products and services were available on each floor.
Maynard Ferguson was a Canadian jazz musician noted for his trumpet work and his stint with Stan Kenton’s orchestra.
Donny & Marie was a ‘70s variety show starring singing Mormon siblings Donny and Marie Osmond. The hosts were 18 and 16 years old when the show first aired.
Among some in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints, the “Wiener Man Song” was rewritten as “I Know a Mormon Boy.”
The tagline for Alien 3 was “The bitch is back.”
Swimmer Esther Williams went into acting after her hopes of competing in the 1940 Olympics were dashed by the outbreak of World War II.
Did we miss a reference? Be sure to let us know in the comments!
The Day the Music Died, so named in the Don McLean song “American Pie,” refers to the Feb. 3, 1959, plane crash that killed Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens, and J.P. “The Big Bopper” Richardson.
Thrush is a maker of auto parts, primarily mufflers; the Glasspack is one particular muffler line they offer.
The Importance of Being Earnest is an Oscar Wilde farce about two young men who have adopted lying as a way of life.
Thanks for watching this fully-annotated presentation of Moon Zero Two.
“Snuggie” here does not refer to the faddish sleeved blankets, but is an alternate term for a wedgie.
“Bein’ Green” is a popular song performed on Sesame Street and The Muppet Show by Jim Henson, voicing Kermit the Frog. Big Bird sang it at Henson’s memorial service.
Disposable diaper brand Pampers were created by Procter & Gamble researcher Vic Mills because he hated changing his new grandchild’s cloth diapers.
“Wedding Bell Blues” was originally written and released by Laura Nyro in 1966, but a 1969 cover by The 5th Dimension became a #1 hit.
Daughter of Judy Garland, the singer/actress Liza Minnelli is known for her starring role in Cabaret and many stints on Broadway.
Armor All is a brand of auto care products launched in 1972. The protectant is designed to keep vinyl, rubber, and plastic looking new.
Basil Fawlty (John Cleese) frequently excused Manuel’s failings to guests with this line.
Florence “Carol Brady” Henderson was a spokesperson for Wesson vegetable oil from 1976-96.
The Nazi Party had many of its uniforms made by the company that eventually became high-fashion menswear designer Hugo Boss.
“He asked me! He asked me!” is the punchline to the Monty Python sketch “Cosmetic Surgery,” after John Cleese asks Graham Chapman to go on a camping holiday with him.
Now it's time to sit back and enjoy…the fully-annotated Moon Zero Two!
Suicide doors is a colloquial term for doors that open front to back. Supposedly they earned their name due to the extreme danger they posed passengers if they popped open in transit.
The tagline for Alien’s 1986 sequel, Aliens, was “This time it’s war.”
Major Kong’s death in Dr. Strangelove is one of the most famous in film history: he straddles a nuclear bomb and rides it, whooping rodeo-style, down to the Soviet target, launching World War III.
The spit-curled mascot for Bob’s Big Boy, a California-based chain of diners, was modeled on a 6-year-old regular customer, Richard Woodruff.
A paraphrase of the famous tagline for the 1979 film Alien: “In space no one can hear you scream.”
“Handle” is CB radio slang for your nickname or call sign.
Probably a reference to Sapphire Stevens, wife of George “Kingfish” Stevens in the long-running radio, film, and TV series Amos ‘n’ Andy.
In bowling, if a player knocks down all the pins in two tries, it’s called a spare (as opposed to a strike: knocking them all down on one go).
Penny arcade Love Tester machines have been around for more than a century. Early machines selected your love level (Blah to Hot Stuff) randomly; later models sometimes measured skin conductance.
The Benny Hill Show was a British sketch comedy series known for high-speed chases set to bouncy music (most famously “Yakety Sax” by Boots Randolph).
Philip Glass is a minimalist composer known for his operas (Einstein on the Beach) as well as his film scores (Koyaanisqatsi, A Brief History of Time).
That means he was born in September. Also, he’s either a Virgo or a Libra.
English actress Julie Andrews first appeared onstage at the age of 10 and made her Broadway debut at 19.
Chuck E. Cheese’s Pizza Time Theatre was the original name for the pizza and games chain founded in 1977 by Nolan Bushnell (who also founded Atari).
The Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center in Houston has been NASA’s flight control station for missions since 1961.
In the late ‘70s, LEGO began producing the Space series: a collection of bricks with an outer space theme. Sets included Rocket Base, Moon Landing, and more, but none specifically called “Moon Base.”
Get the lowdown behind every reference from the Satellite of Love crew.
Siegfried was played by Bernie Kopell, aka Dr. Adam Bricker on The Love Boat and friend Jerry Bauman on the TV sitcom That Girl, which starred Marlo Thomas as a struggling actress in NYC.
Until corn subsidies and federal fuel guidelines forced ethanol into the fuel supply, many gas stations advertised their lack of ethanol because it can damage some engines.
It’s believed “hut” was woven into football thanks to its use as an accent in military marches and orders (e.g., “Atten-hut!”).
Asteroids is Atari’s best-selling arcade game of all time. Released in 1979, it sold more than 70,000 units and earned approximately $500 million in quarters.
I Am Curious (Yellow) is a Swedish film seized in an obscenity case that went to the Supreme Court. The cause of the fuss: a scene in which the heroine gently kisses her lover’s flaccid penis.
In Charlie and the Chocolate Factory, the Oompa-Loompas were originally African pygmies, but Roald Dahl changed later editions to white skin/gold hair. The 1971 film used orange skin/green hair.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Shinyl Vinyl was a line of no-wax floors produced by the Congoleum Corporation in the ‘70s.
If we somehow missed a one, let us know in the comments!
Odor-Eaters were created by Herbert Lapidus in the early ‘70s: an insole made of latex and carbon to neutralize foot odors.
KAOS was the evil organization on the ‘60s spy spoof series Get Smart, represented by Siegfried, the Vice President in Charge of Public Relations and Terror.
Yards of Leather is a porn film apparently invented by Best Brains, because we can’t find a real movie (porn or otherwise) by that title.
In the ‘70s, Coca-Cola ran an animated ad in movie theaters in which a group of penguins discovered “Snack Canyon” and reveled in the delicious beverages they found there.
Magic Screen was the rolling drawing board with the occasional psychedelic display on Pee-wee’s Playhouse. Pee-wee Herman often jumped inside Magic Screen to play.
Dots is a type of gumdrop candy made by Tootsie Roll Industries and first sold in 1945.
The foam finger was invented by high school teacher Geral Fauss, who had the kids in his industrial arts class make plywood versions as a fundraiser in 1978; he later sold foam hands commercially.
Andrews played the title role in the film Thoroughly Modern Millie, as a flapper who sets out to marry her wealthy boss.
Swan Lake is a Russian ballet about a cursed princess composed by Pyotr Tchaikovsky in 1876. Also a reference to MST3K Episode 421, Monster A-Go Go.
Animator Art Clokey created Gumby, the green, lopsided claymation figure, in 1955.
The song is also known as “Weenie Man.”
The Von Trapp Family Choir (aka the Trapp Family Singers) escaped Austria when Germany annexed it in 1938, a story later turned into The Sound of Music.
During live shows on radio and TV, broadcasters often use a tape delay, referred to as a “7-second delay,” to prevent profanity from making it on the air and exposing them to hefty FCC fines.
In the film Airplane!, while airport personnel are reading headlines about the disaster-struck plane, the manic Johnny peers over their shoulders and squeals, “There’s a sale at Penney’s!”
In the early ‘70s, the 19th-century game Reversi, with its black & white pieces, was marketed as Othello, named after the Shakespeare play in which the Moor Othello conflicts with the Caucasian Iago.
Glam rocker David Bowie’s hit single “Space Oddity,” aka “Ground Control to Major Tom,” was released 5 days before Apollo 11 launched and 10 days before it landed on the Moon.
“Zactlies” is a bit of charming slang: after a night of drinking, one wakes up with a taste in one’s mouth (or a smell on one’s breath) that tastes (or smells) “zactly” like one’s, ahem, anus.
“Raspberry Red,” “Lemony Yellow,” “Blueberry Blue,” and “Orangey Orange” were names for some of the original 8 colors of Trix cereal, as mentioned in their ads.
The syndicated country variety show Hee Haw saw appearances by nearly every major star in country music, including Johnny Cash, Willie Nelson, and Loretta Lynn. It ran from 1969-1992.
Horn player Chuck Mangione had an international instrumental hit in 1978 with “Feels So Good.” He was also a recurring character on the animated sitcom King of the Hill.
“Cheese it!” (meaning “Quiet!” or “Stop it!”) first appeared in print in O. Henry’s 1908 book The Voice of the City, but it was being used in the 1800s in the U.K.
“Houston, Tranquility Base here. The Eagle has landed” was astronaut Neil Armstrong’s first non-technical message to Earth once the Apollo 11 Lunar Module landed on the Moon.
Other colors that have been added to Trix cereal over the years: Grapity Purple, Banana Yellow, Strawberry Red, and Raspberry Blue.
Bury My Heart at Wounded Knee is a 1970 book by Dee Brown on the history of American Indians in the late 1800s. At the Wounded Knee Massacre in 1890, 150 unarmed Sioux were killed by the US Cavalry.
Rock ‘Em Sock ‘Em Robots was a popular game first made in 1964—basically, two robots in a boxing ring, and you moved handles to get the robots to hit each other.
In John Steinbeck’s Of Mice and Men, the strong but simple-minded Lennie Small has a love for soft things (especially rabbits) but tends to accidentally hurt them.
In one scene, the “Nowhere Man,” Jeremy, is kidnapped and taken to the Sea of Holes; one of these holes ends up in Ringo’s pocket.
An imitation of Colonel Wilhelm Klink (played by Werner Klemperer), the inept commander of the German POW camp on the CBS sitcom Hogan’s Heroes.
“Listen to What the Man Said” is a 1975 hit single by Wings, written by Paul and Linda McCartney.
“Trix are for kids” was the longtime tagline for the cereal, due to the constant attempts of the Trix Rabbit (introduced in 1959) to get his paws on the cereal, only to be thwarted by meddling kids.
Breakout was a 1976 Atari arcade game. Steve Wozniak and Steve Jobs, in their pre-Apple days, built a prototype of the game for Atari.
The Garden Weasel is a cultivator designed to break up soil and root up weeds. It has been advertised on TV since 1976.
Porta-Potty is one of several brand names for portable toilets usually placed at outdoor events.
The phrase “visible panty line,” or VPL, appears to have originated within the military; it was popularized by the Woody Allen film Annie Hall.
Randolph Mantooth is best known for playing paramedic Johnny Gage in the ‘70s TV drama Emergency!
The Colt 45 phrase was parodied in the film Anchorman with the slogan for Sex Panther cologne: “Sixty percent of the time, it works every time.”
Playtex Cross Your Heart Bras is a line of bras made since the ‘50s; in the ‘70s buxom actress Jane Russell was their spokesperson.
The Colt 45 slogan was used primarily in ads from the ‘80s featuring actor Billy Dee Williams.
Probably a reference to the 1973 Jim Croce song “Roller Derby Queen.” Roller derby began in the ‘30s as a skating marathon; it died out in the early ‘70s and was revived 30 years later.
An imitation of how Looney Tunes mainstay Yosemite Sam swears.
In Tennessee Williams’ play The Glass Menagerie, the character of Jim is Laura’s “gentleman caller.”
Art Clokey also created Davey and Goliath for the Lutheran Church.
Actor Zero Mostel is best known today for his role in the 1968 film The Producers. He was blacklisted in the ‘50s after refusing to name names before the commie-hunters at HUAC.
“Crotch rocket” is a slang term for a sport motorcycle, usually of the annoying, high-pitched variety.
NBC announcer Don Pardo supplied the introduction for Saturday Night Live for 38 years, until his death in 2014. He worked at the network for 70 years.
Major T.J. “King” Kong, played by Slim Pickens, is a character in the 1964 Cold War satire Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb.
